(213, 1, '2019-05-21 09:00:33', '2019-05-21 09:00:33', '[vc_row css=\".vc_custom_1558257009068{margin-bottom: 50px !important;}\"][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=\"Sustainability\" font_container=\"tag:h1|text_align:center\" use_theme_fonts=\"yes\"][vc_separator][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h2>OVERVIEW: Steps to creating business sustainability</h2>\r\nBusiness and economic sustainability are considered essential for survival of the human race and for the maintenance of the earth as a habitable environment. Damage is being caused by businesses and that damage needs to be stopped, prevented, and repaired if life, as it is currently understood, is to prevail. For businesses to transform to a new paradigm and stay viable, the following four-point plan is considered essential for their development and possibly their survival. A new business paradigm, or zeitgeist, is certainly essential for the survival of humanity as we know it.\r\n<ol style=\"color: white;\">\r\n 	<li>Figure out what phase (or stage) the company is currently at. This is Point A</li>\r\n 	<li>Improve the Business: make the business Strategically Sustainable. This is Point B</li>\r\n 	<li>What is the Business Case for Sustainability?</li>\r\n 	<li>Develop a plan to get from Point A to Point B for all the key dimensions of the company.</li>\r\n 	<li>Develop a monitoring system to keep the company at Point B</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_single_image image=\"129\" img_size=\"full\"][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h3>Step 1 : Point A</h3>\r\nFigure out what phase the company is currently at. This is Point A\r\n\r\nUsing the 6 phase model\r\n<em><strong>Phase 1:</strong></em>Rejection  Dont know and dont care\r\n<em><strong>Phase 2:</strong></em>Non-responsive  Aware of the issue, but still dont care  for many reasons\r\n<em><strong>Phase 3:</strong></em>Compliance/Risk Reduction  only doing what is legally/formally required\r\n<em><strong>Phase 4:</strong></em>Efficiency: doing some things better as a cost reduction plan\r\n<em><strong>Phase 5:</strong></em>Adopting an action plan to become strategically sustainable in all dimensions\r\n<em><strong>Phase 6:</strong></em>Being ideologically sustainable in every aspect of business[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h3>Step 2: Point B</h3>\r\n<em><strong>The objective is to raise the company to Phase 5: Strategically Sustainable. This is Point B</strong></em>\r\n\r\nIdeally, all companies should operate at Phase 6 but this may be unrealistic for many businesses as their core operations are unsustainable in the long term (oil, coal etc), or the products theyre producing (cheap plastic goods, disposable batteries, plastic shopping bags etc) are unsustainable.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h3>Step 3: Plan</h3>\r\nDevelop a plan to get from Point A to Point B for all key dimensions\r\n\r\n<strong><em>1. This involves a deep analysis of everything the business does,</em></strong>all aspects of its operations including production processes, product development, supply chain activities including materials and processes, its marketing and distribution activities, and end-of-life product disposal issues.\r\n<em><strong>2. The plan takes into account all the technical, financial, and social dimensions</strong></em>of the business as well as corporate governance and the use of non-renewable non-reusable non-recyclable resources.\r\n<em><strong>3. The plan takes into account all externalities</strong></em>required for the product to be sustainable as well as all non-beneficial outputs such as GHGs, eco-destruction, and cross-contamination issues.\r\n<em><strong>4. The plan is time framed to allow for all changes to be made</strong></em>on a programmed basis with all costs and benefits captured and dealt with on an ongoing basis.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h3>Step 4: Monitoring System</h3>\r\nDevelop a monitoring system to keep the company at Point B\r\n1.The monitoring system must address all issues in the business and must aim at keeping the business functionally operational on a do no harm basis for all its operational, financial, investment, social, societal, and ecological activities.\r\n2. The monitoring system must identify all chemicals, minerals, elements and parts that are used in all manufacturing processes and all products, and assumes total responsibility for all these issues for the whole-of-life of these issues. The monitoring system has one boundary and that is from raw material extraction through all processes to ultimate decomposition.\r\n3. Indicators of performance are generally used and standard indicators such as Global Reporting Initiatives (GRI) or self-created indicators can be adopted where the purpose of each indicator is to show conformance to or deviations from all measures of good practice.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width=\"stretch_row\" css=\".vc_custom_1558258265860{background-color: #008080 !important;}\"][vc_column][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"5/6\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<h2 style=\"color: white;\">DOWNLOAD FILE FOR STRATEGIC SUSTAINABILITY &amp; RISK MANAGEMENT</h2>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/6\"][vc_btn title=\"Download Now\" color=\"black\" size=\"lg\" align=\"left\" link=\"url:http%3A%2F%2Flocalhost%2Funderscore_2019%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2019%2F05%2FSSRM.June_.2017.V2.docx|||\"][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=\"What we can do for sustainability?\" font_container=\"tag:h1|text_align:center\" use_theme_fonts=\"yes\"][vc_separator el_width=\"50\"][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Business sustainability is critical for survival of the human race</em></strong>and for the maintenance of the earth as a habitable environment. Damage is being caused by businesses and that damage needs to be stopped, prevented, and repaired if life, as it is currently understood, is to prevail.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<em><strong>Businesses certainly have an economic imperative</strong></em>however this imperative is for societies in general and not for the business. People need the planet to sustain life so that any planet-damaging business is therefore not in the best interests of the people the business is economically serving.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Businesses are only valid if they truly serve their primary purposes </em></strong>first and foremost and their economic interests second. For businesses to transform to a new paradigm and stay viable, the following four point plan is considered essential for their development and possibly their survival.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=\"Six Phases of Sustainibiity\" font_container=\"tag:h2|text_align:center\" use_theme_fonts=\"yes\"][vc_separator el_width=\"50\"][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=\"sus\" width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text el_class=\"sus\"]<strong><em>Phase 1: Rejection</em></strong>\r\n The environment is regarded as exploitable\r\n Hostility to environmental activities\r\n Production and extraction processes destroy future capacity or damage the ecosystem\r\n Polluting by-products are discharged\r\n Employees and sub-contractors are regarded as a resource to be used\r\n Compliance required of workforce backed up by threats/force\r\n Little training; few career prospects for employees[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=\"sus\" width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Phase 2: Non-responsiveness</em></strong>\r\n Ecological environment not considered as a relevant input\r\n Financial and technological factors dominate business strategy\r\n Efficiency rules\r\n Environmental resources wasted and costs not considered\r\n Training in the technical area only\r\n Wider social responsibility and community concern is ignored[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=\"sus\" width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Phase 3: Compliance</em></strong>\r\n Senior management see the need to comply with environmental laws\r\n Attempt to limit the liability of the enterprise\r\n Obvious environmental abuses eliminated\r\n Employer saw as a decent employer\r\n Efforts at safety workplace standards appear\r\n Organization practices benevolent paternalism\r\n Awareness that negative community publicity may be harmful so some community concerns addressed[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=\"sus\" width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Phase 4: Efficiency</em></strong>\r\n Environmental practice seen as a cost\r\n Review of environmental inputs and waste to minimise expenditure in these areas\r\n Environmental issues that do not generate avoidable costs ignored\r\n ISO 14001 procedure may be in place\r\n Coherent HR systems practised\r\n Team work &amp; training acknowledged\r\n Funding of community projects with a positive return for the company[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=\"sus\" width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Phase 5: Strategic Sustainability</em></strong>\r\n Proactive environmental strategies seen as a strategic advantage\r\n Product redesign to reuse/recycle materials\r\n Environmental outputs are engineered to be useful\r\n Leadership sought through environmentally friendly products and processes\r\n Workforce diversity sought and used\r\n Social capital equals strategic advantage\r\n Flexible workplace to maximize talent use[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner el_class=\"sus\" width=\"1/3\"][vc_column_text]<strong><em>Phase 6: Ideological Commitment</em></strong>\r\n Actively promotes sustainability\r\n Environmental best practice is espoused\r\n Organisation thinks about sustainability throughout its entire operations\r\n Organisation uses its influence with government to promote sustainability\r\n Promoter of diversity and work/life balance\r\n It has a corporate ethnical position and action plan to pursue human welfare and equitable and socially just practices[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'Sustainability', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '121-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-05-21 09:00:33', '2019-05-21 09:00:33', '', 121, 'http://localhost/underscore_2019/2019/05/21/121-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
